data.value: Saturn is the second largest planet, and the sixth planet from the Sun. It’s also the farthest planet from Earth still visible to the naked human eye. Saturn's most well known feature, however, are it’s rings. The other gas giants in the solar system also have rings, but Saturn's rings are the most prominent. These magnificent rings are made almost entirely of a mixture of water-ice chunks and rocks. They can be as large as a house, or as small as a grain of sugar. These rings are believed to be leftover debris from comets, asteroids or shattered moons. It's been theorized that these rings could also be the leftover debris from other dwarf planets similar in size to Pluto. Despite its size, Saturn is the least dense of all the planets. In fact, if you were able to put the entire planet in a pool of water, it’d float. The atmosphere of Saturn is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium. This kind of atmosphere makes life as we know it impossible to exist, but some of Saturns moons have been theorized to be able to support life. Saturn currently has 53 known moons, with 29 moons awaiting confirmation. That's 82 moons! It takes 29 years for Saturn to orbit earth, and its day cycle lasts a short 10.5 hours. In fact, the planet’s high-speed spin causes Saturn to bulge at its equator and flatten at its poles. Saturn was named after the Roman god of agriculture and wealth, who was also the father of Jupiter.
